   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"
                           ><title>Oronooko</title></hi>]. <note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><title>Oronooko</title>; A Tragedy, In Five Acts; By <ref
                                 target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Thomas Southern</ref>. As
                              Performed at the Theatre Royal, <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden"
                                 >Covent Garden</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers
                              From the Prompt Book. With Remarks by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald</ref></title></hi>.
                        Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi
                           rendition="#italics"><title level="m">The British Theatre; or, A
                              Collection of Plays, Which Are Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>, and <ref
                                 target="people.html#Haymarket">Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the
                              Authority of the Managers from the Prompt Books. With Biographical and
                              Critical Remarks, by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                                 Inchbald.</ref></title></hi> In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. VII. <hi
                           rendition="#italics">
                           <title>Isabella</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Oroonoko</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Distressed Mother</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Zara</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#GustavIKingofSweden">Gustavus
                              Vasa</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and
                        Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play was staged
                        at the <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre Royal, Drury Lane</ref>
                        in November of 1695. Bernadette D. Woodburn, Laura DeWitt, and Mary A.
                        Waters edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The Criticism
                           Archive</hi>. </note></title>
                  <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>The valuable half of this drama, which is the tragic part, is founded neither upon
               fictitious characters nor events. Such an African prince, as Oroonoko, stolen from
               his native kingdom of Angola, was actually brought to an English settlement in the
               West Indies, and sold for a slave.<note>Researchers have debated whether or not <ref
                     target="people.html#BehnAphra">Aphra Behn</ref>, the author of the 1688 novel
                     <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Oronooko</title></hi> which served as the basis
                  of <ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Southerne</ref>'s theatrical
                  adaptation, may have met a figure similar to the character of Oronooko during a
                  visit to Surinam, a short-lived English colony in present-day Suriname in South
                  America. There is some disagreement, however, whether <ref
                     target="people.html#BehnAphra">Behn</ref> ever visited South
               America.</note></p>
            <p>This pitiable occurrence took place in the reign of <ref
                  target="people.html#CharlesIIKingofEngland">Charles II</ref>. at the time that
                  <ref target="people.html#BehnAphra">Mrs. Behn</ref>, the well-known dramatic
               writer, whom <ref target="people.html#PopeAlexander">Pope</ref> has honoured by a
                  satire,<note>From <ref target="people.html#PopeAlexander">Alexander Pope</ref>'s
                     <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The First Epistle of the Second Book of <ref
                           target="people.html#Horace">Horace</ref>, Imitated</title></hi>: "The
                  stage how loosely does Astræea tread / Who fairly puts all characters to bed"
                  (1737, p. 17). Astræea was the pastoral pseudonym <ref
                     target="people.html#BehnAphra">Aphra Behn</ref> gave herself while working for
                     <ref target="people.html#CharlesIIKingofEngland">King Charles II</ref>. </note>
               resided at Surinam with her family; her father having been appointed lieutenant
               general of that settlement, and of thirty neighbouring islands.<note><ref
                     target="people.html#BehnAphra">Behn</ref>'s early biographers believed <ref
                     target="people.html#BehnAphra">Behn</ref> to be the unnamed narrator of <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>Oronooko</title></hi>, whose father is the
                  lieutenant general of the settlement.</note></p>
            <p>It was at Surinam, that <ref target="people.html#BehnAphra">Mrs. Behn</ref>, not only
               saw, but became intimately acquainted with the unfortunate, but still proud and
               dignified, Oroonoko. She was witness to his bravery and skill in arms, upon the
               occasion of some danger threatening the island: and she beheld his humility and
               moderation, when all his martial feats were performed, and tranquility restored. She
               knew his Imoinda,<note>The daughter of an African general who gave his life to
                  protect Oronooko, Imoinda is Oronooko's love interest.</note> and saw with delight
               their rapturous affection for each other.</p>
            <p>On the return of <ref target="people.html#BehnAphra">Mrs. Behn</ref> to England, she
               published the memoirs of those ill-fated lovers; from<lb/><fw type="sig"><hi
                     rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw><pb n="4"/> which publication, <ref
                  target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Southern</ref> has selected materials for
               this pathetic tragedy.</p>
            <p>Whether the comic characters are taken from persons in real life, or from the poet's
               fancy, is not known: nor is it of much consequence from whence they came, as they can
               do no great degree of honour to their birth-place.</p>
            <p>The repulsive qualities of some of those characters, joined to the little which has
               been allotted for the heroine to perform, have been obstacles to the attraction of
               this drama, and it is seldom acted. Yet, some years past, Mr. Pope,<note>Not to be
                  confused with the author of the same name, <ref target="people.html#PopeAlexander"
                     >Alexander Pope</ref>, the Mr. Pope to whom Inchbald here refers is actor and
                  painter Alexander Pope (1763-1835), who debuted in this play four decades after
                  the author <ref target="people.html#PopeAlexander">Alexander Pope's</ref> death in
                  1744.</note> in his very first appearance upon any stage, encountered, and
               triumphantly overcame, all impediments to the favourable reception of
                  <title>Oroonoko</title>; and made the play so impressive, by his talents in the
               representation of that character, that for many nights it drew to the theatre a
               crowded audience. His acting was remarkably fine in the last scene; whilst his youth,
               person, deportment, and even features, gave an accurate portraiture of one of
               Africa's princely sons.</p>
            <p>But could the ancient <ref target="people.html#Roscius">Roscius</ref> ascend from his
               grave to personate the hero of this piece, there is a great mercantile town in
               England, whose opulent inhabitants would not permit the play to appear in their
               magnificent theatre. The tragedy of "<title>Oroonoko</title>" is never acted in
               Liverpool, for the very reason why it ought to be acted there oftener than at any
               other place&#8212;The merchants of the great city acquire their riches by the slave
                  trade.<note>Liverpool was the foremost English slaving port of the 18<hi
                     rendition="#sup">th</hi> century.</note></p>
            <p>If any defect can be attributed to <ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas"
                  >Southern</ref> in the<pb n="5"/> tragic fable, either of this play or of
                  "<title>Isabella,</title>" it is, that in the one, his first male character wants
               importance, and in the other, his principal female. Still, in both plays, he makes
               his tale, a tale of woe, though only a single personage becomes the object of deep
               concern.</p>
            <p>That the poet <ref target="people.html#GrayThomas">Gray</ref> was an admirer of this
               tragedy, is seen in a letter of his to <ref target="people.html#WalpoleHorace">Horace
                  Walpole</ref>, dated, Burnham in Buckinghamshire, 1737; wherein he says, "We have
               old <ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Mr. Southern</ref>, at a gentleman's
               house a little way off, who often comes to see us. He is now seventy years old, and
               has almost wholly lost his memory; but is as agreeable an old man as can be; at
               least, I persuade myself so, when I look at him, and think of <title>Isabella</title>
               and <title>Oroonoko</title>."<note>See Mason's <title>Life of <ref
                        target="people.html#GrayThomas">Gray</ref></title>. [Inchbald's note]. <ref
                     target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> slightly alters this quotation
                  from William Mason's <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Memoirs of the Life and
                        Writings of <ref target="people.html#GrayThomas">Mr. Gray</ref></title></hi>
                  (1775, pp. 24-25).</note></p>
            <p><ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Southern</ref> is an exception from most
               poets, in having been wealthy; but he procured some of his wealth by a means, which
               all poets should rather submit to poverty than employ: he printed tickets on his
               benefit nights as an author, and even urged their sale among his noble and
               distinguished friends. Thus, vilely reducing himself to dependence, in order to
               become rich; in lieu of honourably seeking riches, that he might become
                  independent.<note>This account of <ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas"
                     >Southerne</ref>'s finances apperas in <ref
                     target="people.html#CibberTheophilus">Theophilus Cibber</ref>'s <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Lives of the Poets of Great Britain and
